Hempling’s  Direct Testimony that include HCTS  Information . 
The Partners bring this Motion  pursuant to Administrative Law Judge Megan McKenzie’s 
December 5, 2024 Protective Order and December 16, 2024 Protective Order for Highly 
Confidential Trade Secret Data, Minn. R. 1400.5500, Minn. R. 1400.6600, and Minn. R. Civ. P. 
37.02(b) . The Partner’s Motion  is supported by the attached Memorandum in Support of Motion 
to Revoke Access  and Strike .

MEMORANDUM OF LAW IN SUPPORT OF MOTION TO REVOKE ACCESS  AND 
STRIKE  DIRECT TESTIMONY  OF SCOTT HEMPLING  
 
Canada Pension Plan Investment Board (“CPP Investments ”) and Global Infrastructure 
Management, LLC ( “GIP” and together with CPP Investments  the “Partners”) file this Motion to 
Revoke Access  and Strike in response to the egregious breach of the Highly Confidential 
Protective Order committed  by Citizens Utility Board (“CUB”) witness Scott Hempling on 
February 6, 2025.  The Partners hereby move the Administrative Law Judge  (“ALJ”)  for an Order 
(1) revoking the access of Hempling to  Highly Confidential Trade Secret  (“HCTS”) Info rmation ; 
and (2) striking the  specific portions of Hempling’s testimony that include HCTS Information.  
 
I. BACKGROUND  
The Protective Orders  
This motion stems from disclosure of protected data and highly sensitive commercial 
information  subject to  two protective order s issued by ALJ Megan McKenzie  in this proceeding. 
The first protective order (“TS Protective Order”)1 governs  the disclosure of Protected Data . 
Protected Data includes Trade Secret data as defined in Minn. Stat. § 13.37, subd. 1(b). The second 
 
1 In the Matter of the Petition of Minnesota Power for Acquisition of ALLETE by  Canada Pension Plan Investment 
Board and Global Infrastructure Partners , OAH Docket No. 25-2500 -40339, MPUC Docket No. E015/PA -24-198, 
Protective Order (Dec. 5, 2024), eDocket No. 202412 -212750 -01. A copy of the TS Protective Order is included as 
Exhibit 1 . 
PUBLIC DOCUMENT – NOT PUBLIC DATA HAS BEEN EXCISED  
 4 
 protective order, Protective Order for Highly Confidential Trade Secret Data2 (“HCTS Protective 
Order ” and, together with the TS Protective O rder, “Protective Orders”) , govern s the disclosure of 
HCTS  Information . The HCTS designation was created by agreement among the parties to 
establish additional protections for a small subset of critically sensitive documents that would 
cause a “serious business risk” if disclosed.3 
To that end, HCTS Information  is available only to entities that are formal parties  to this 
proceeding. Within a party, access to HCTS Information  is limited to , in most cases,  outside 
counsel and retained consultants  who have executed Exhibit A to the HCTS Protective Order , and  
HCTS “cannot be shared with the other employees of any receiving Party .”4 Given the sensitivity 
of the data at issue, the HCTS Protective Order provides that parties must “make a good faith effort 
to limit the number of individuals who have access to HCTS Information to no more than two 
individuals.”5 Protected Data, including HCTS Information, is to be “[u]sed solely for the purposes 
of this proceeding, and not used or disclosed for any other purpose or in any other manner, without 
an order from the [ALJ] .”6 The HCTS Protective Order requires Party Representatives who receive 
HCTS Information to  “securely maintain the documents and any notes reflecting their contents by 
means appropriate to the medium” and handle the HCTS Information “in a manner suitable to 
protect its confidentiality consistent with the requirements” of the HCTS Protective Order.7   
 
 
2 Protective Order for Highly Confidential Trade Secret Data (Dec. 16, 2024), eDocket No. 202412 -212992 -01. A 
copy of the HCTS Protective Order is included as Exhibit 2 . 
3 HCTS Information includes “a) commercial arrangements or agreements  that may affect future negotiations or 
transactions of the disclosing party; b) commercially sensitive investment, financing, or forward -looking business 
plans, analysis, and/or models by or for a disclosing party; c) commercially sensitive data related t o specific customers 
or customer groups; or, d) commercially sensitive proprietary information of entities other than the disclosing party.”  
HCTS Protective Order  ¶ 3. 
4 Id.  ¶ 8. 
5 Id. 
6 TS Protective Order ¶ 2. 
7 HCTS Protective Order ¶ 9.

 5 
 Hempling’s  Receipt of Protected Data  
Scott Hempling of Scott Hempling Attorney at Law, LLC, was provided access to Trade 
Secret  and HCTS Information solely as a result of his role as an expert witness  for CUB . Hempling 
and CUB are subject to the terms of these Protective Orders.8 Hempling holds himself out as an 
expert on matters related to utility acquisitions.9 It appears that a major part of Hempling’s business 
is testifying  in opposition to acquisitions of utility companies .  
On December 17, 2024, CUB filed three Exhibit A Non -Disclosure Agreement s to obtain 
access to HCTS Information. Because requesting access for three individuals was inconsistent with 
the intent of the HCTS Protective Order that CUB had stipulated to, CUB withdrew its request  on 
December 20, 2024. On the same date, CUB filed Exhibit A Non -Disclosure Agreement s signed 
by CUB’s counsel and Hempling  to obtain access to HCTS Information . Access to HCTS 
Information provided in response to discovery requests was given to CUB’s counsel and Hempling 
no later than December 26, 2024.  
After access was provided , Hempling repeatedly breached the Protective Orders, as 
described below, which now requires the Partners to seek relief.   
 
The Breaches  
On February 4, 2025, Hempling filed Direct Testimony on behalf of CUB.   Hempling’s 
Direct  Testimony  contains a substantial amount of HCTS  Information .10 For example, Hempling 
 
8 The signed Exhibit A to the TS Protective Order and the HCTS Protective Order for CUB’s counsel, Brian 
Edstrom, and Scott Hempling were filed in the docket  for this proceeding . The Exhibit As for the TS Protective 
Order for Edstrom and Hempling were filed on December 17, 2024, eDocket N o. 202412 -213106 -02. The Exhibit 
As for the HCTS Protective Order for Edstrom and Hempling were filed on December 20, 2024, eDocket Nos. 
202412 -213261 -03 and202412 -213261 -02. Hempling’s NDA s are attached as Exhibit  3. 
9 See www.scotthemplinglaw.com .

20252 -215065 -02.

 discusses [HCTS INFORMATION NOT FOR ALLETE BEGINS …]

INFORMATION NOT FOR ALLETE ENDS]  
Upon review, the Partners determined that both footnote 8 and 9, on page 6, included public 
references to the content of HCTS documents.  This was particularly troubling since the Direct 
Testimony  is also replete with remarks suggesting that Hempling does not believe the Partners 
should be permitted  to protect their commercially sensitive data from public disclosure.11 The 
Partners were compelled to contact CUB and request that the testimony be withdrawn and replaced 
by a version that was properly redacted. Unfortunately, it is not possible to know who downloaded 
the publicly available testimony during the time it was available on the eFi ling system.  This 
handling of HCTS Information was not consistent with the Protective Orders.  
 On the evening of February 6, 2025 , the Partners learned that Hempling breached the 
Protective Orders again  and in a much more serious manner  by12 [NOT PUBLIC DATA  BEGINS 
…]

that there is more.” ). All of th e documents  Hempling complains about include  information that is protected from 
disclosure by Minnesota law and the Protective Orders.

to obtain information from CUB. Based on the information CUB has provided , the Partners believe 
the following facts to be true.

Because the Partners’ HCTS Information was uploaded to the  public  internet, it is likely impossible 
to ever verify that it has been completely destroyed. The damage has been done and there is no 
way of clawing back the HCTS Information that was released.  
This sequence of events represents multiple breaches of the Protective Orders. First,  
Hempling or employees working at his direction obtained and  uploaded the Partners’ HCTS 
Information to the internet  for purposes other than submitting testimony to this tribunal , and then 
further advertised the link on social media . This is an egregious breach of the Protective Order s. 
Regardless of whether it was inadvertent, it is clear that Hempling shared the information with a 
person who was not entitled to receive it, and was not treating the Partners’ HCTS Information 
with the care  that a reasonable person would apply, much less the professional care required of a 
licensed attorney —as Hempling is —or the heightened security required by the Protective Orders . 

PUBLIC DOCUMENT – NOT PUBLIC DATA HAS BEEN EXCISED  
 9 
  Second, Hempling signed an Exhibit A NDA agreeing in writing that he would use the 
HCTS Information he received from the Partners “solely for the purpose of this proceeding and 
for no other purpose.”14 Hempling is in the business of opposing acquisitions of public utilities 
across the country.  These facts demonstrate  that Hempling’s motivation for uploading the 
document to his personal website was marketing  on his own behalf , not for any purpose related to 
this proceeding.   
Third , the information provided to the Partners indicates  that an individual  employed by 
Scott Hempling Attorney at Law had access to the Partners’ HCTS Information, but had not signed 
an Exhibit A NDA permitting that access. The HCTS Protective Order clearly states that HCTS 
Information must not be shared with anyone who has not signed the appropriate  NDA. In 
particular, by signing Exhibit A to the HCTS Protective Order, Hempling agreed “not to disclose 
to any person or entity not authorized to receive materials designated [HCTS  Information ]…or 
any copies or extracts of information derived therefrom.”15  At the request of the Partners, 
Hempling has confirmed that any copies held by his employee  have been destroyed and that the 
employee’s  access has been removed, but this disregard  or lack of care with respect to  the 
provisions of the Protective Orders is a clear breach.  
As the ALJ is aware, the Parties submitted a stipulated set of protective orders, including 
the HCTS Protective Order. From the outset of this proceeding, the Partners were very concerned 
about releasing information that is highly competitively sensitive a nd that would cause material 
harm to  the Partners if released to the public . This concern was conveyed to the Parties through 
multiple meetings and discussions regarding the Protective Orders.  The Protective Orders were 
carefully crafted to mitigate the chances of this information being made public. Unfortunately,  
 
14 TS Protective Order , Exhibit A  Nondisclosure Agreement . 
15 HCTS Protective Order, Exhibit A Protective Order for Highly Confidential Trade Secret Data.   
PUBLIC DOCUMENT – NOT PUBLIC DATA HAS BEEN EXCISED  
 10 
 with respect to Hempling and his employee  it is now clear that the Protective Orders are not 
sufficient  to assure protection of confidential information , and additional relief  is needed . 
II. THE ADMINISTRATIVE LAW JUDGE  HAS AUTHORITY TO ORDER 
REMEDIES FOR VIOLATIONS OF THE PROTECTIVE ORDER S 
 
The Partners move for relief against Hempling for his violations of the Protective Order s.  
Under the terms of the Protective Order s, any violation of orders or their accompanying  Exhibit A 
constitute “ a violation of an order of the Commission. ”16  The Protective Order s further state that 
“[e]ach party bears the responsibility to ensure that each of its representatives shall perform all 
obligations under this Protective Order .”17  Parties, including the Partners , also “retain[] the right 
to seek appropriate legal or equitable remedies in the event that any party or its representatives fail 
to perform any obligations under this Protective Order. ”18 
The ALJ has the authority  to hear this motion under the terms of the Protective Order s, 
Minnesota  Rules , and the Minnesota Rules of Civil Procedure. Pursuant to Minn. R. 1400.5500 , 
the ALJ is empowered to “hear and rule on motions .” Minnesota Rules Chapter 1400 does not 
contain specific provisions to control this situation, so the ALJ may look to the Minnesota Rules 
of Civil Procedure .19 Minnesota Rule of Civil Procedure 37.02 (b) sets forth the procedure that 
applies when a party violat es a discovery  order .  In relevant part, this rule states : 
If a party or an officer, director, employee, or managing agent of a party or a person 
designated in Rule  30.02 (f) or  31.01  to testify on behalf of a party fails to obey an 
order to provide or permit discovery, including an order made pursuant to 
Rule  35 or 37.01 , the court in which the action is pending may make such orders in 
regard to the failure as are just, and among others the following:  
. . . 
 
16 HCTS Protective Order ¶  17; TS Protective Order ¶ 26.  
17 HCTS Protective Order ¶  17; TS Protective Order ¶ 26. 
18 HCTS Protective Order  ¶ 17. 
19 Minn. R. 1400.6600  (“In ruling on motions where parts 1400.5100 to 1400.8400 are silent, the judge shall apply the 
Rules of Civil Procedure for the District Court for Minnesota to the extent that it is determined appropriate in order to 
promote a fair and expeditious proceeding. ”). 
PUBLIC DOCUMENT – NOT PUBLIC DATA HAS BEEN EXCISED  
 11 
 (2) An order refusing to allow the disobedient party to support or oppose 
designated claims or defenses, or prohibiting that party from introducing designated 
matters in evidence;  
(3) An order striking pleadings or parts thereof, staying further proceedings 
until the order is obeyed, dismissing the action or proceeding or any part thereof, 
or rendering a judgment by default against the disobedient party;20 
GIP and CPP Investments  therefore request that the ALJ issue an order to : (1) revoke Hempling’s 
access to HCTS  Information; and, (2) strike the portions of Hempling’s Direct Testimony  that refer 
to HCTS  Informa tion. 
III. HEMPLING’S ACCESS TO HCTS INFORMATION  SHOULD BE REVOKED    
 
The Partners are entitled to seek equitable remedies  for unauthorized  disclosure  of HCTS 
Information  based on several provisions of the Protective Orders . First, the TS Protective Order, 
which applies to HCTS Information, provides that a Party may object to providing protected data 
to a specific expert or wit ness.21 While that objection is normally filed before protected data is

agencies” has the same meaning as “state agency” under Minn. Stat. § 13.02, subd. 17

government agencies shall be strictly controlled by the terms of this Protective Order. The 
parties other than governmental agencies are hereafter referred to in this Protective Order 
as parties, persons, recipients, or entities.

Public Utilities Commission, the Office of Administrative Hearings (OAH), the Office of the 
Attorney General, the Minnesota Department of Commerce, the Minnesota Department of

rules and procedures.

The designating party shall limit the HCTS designation to those portions of the document

II. THE ADMINISTRATIVE LAW JUDGE  HAS AUTHORITY TO ORDER 
REMEDIES FOR VIOLATIONS OF THE PROTECTIVE ORDER S 
 
The Partners move for relief against Hempling for his violations of the Protective Order s.  
Under the terms of the Protective Order s, any violation of orders or their accompanying  Exhibit A 
constitute “ a violation of an order of the Commission. ”16  The Protective Order s further state that 
“[e]ach party bears the responsibility to ensure that each of its representatives shall perform all 
obligations under this Protective Order .”17  Parties, including the Partners , also “retain[] the right 
to seek appropriate legal or equitable remedies in the event that any party or its representatives fail 
to perform any obligations under this Protective Order. ”18 
The ALJ has the authority  to hear this motion under the terms of the Protective Order s, 
Minnesota  Rules , and the Minnesota Rules of Civil Procedure. Pursuant to Minn. R. 1400.5500 , 
the ALJ is empowered to “hear and rule on motions .” Minnesota Rules Chapter 1400 does not 
contain specific provisions to control this situation, so the ALJ may look to the Minnesota Rules 
of Civil Procedure .19 Minnesota Rule of Civil Procedure 37.02 (b) sets forth the procedure that 
applies when a party violat es a discovery  order .  In relevant part, this rule states : 
If a party or an officer, director, employee, or managing agent of a party or a person 
designated in Rule  30.02 (f) or  31.01  to testify on behalf of a party fails to obey an 
order to provide or permit discovery, including an order made pursuant to 
Rule  35 or 37.01 , the court in which the action is pending may make such orders in 
regard to the failure as are just, and among others the following:

The Partners are entitled to seek equitable remedies  for unauthorized  disclosure  of HCTS

to a specific expert or wit ness.21 While that objection is normally filed before protected data is

at this time. The TS Protective Order provides tha t once an objection is filed, no access shall be 
provided until ordered by the ALJ  and this provisions applies to HCTS Information as well .22 
Second, the HCTS Protective Order provides that if a party discloses protected data, 
including HCTS Information, to an unauthorized person and the parties are unable to resolve the 
issue, a party may file a motion with the ALJ for relief.23 The Partners  appreciate the efforts of 
CUB’s counsel to contain the damage to the extent possible, but CUB has informed the Partners 
that it is impossible to determine who accessed or downloaded the Partners’ HCTS Information,

I am writing to discuss a host of issues related to Global Infrastructure Partners’ (GIP) 
response to DOC IR 0012 and 0013, and Canadian Pension Plan Investment Board’s (CPP) response to DOC IR 0060.  Following the in camera review offered by GIP and CPP (collectively, the Partners), the Minnesota Department of Commerce has considered the Partners’ offered rationale for offering limited information in support of its claims of privilege, the accuracy of the Partners’ most recent privilege/redaction log (DOC 0003.03 Supp 3 TS), and the redaction of information from responsive documents for reasons other than privilege . After 
careful consideration , the Department continues to find the Partners’ response unacceptable. The 
Department renews its request for t he production of responsive documents with no redactions 
other than those for which a prima facie privilege claim is provided on an appropriate privilege log.  Please provide any supplementation of your clients’ responses on or before close of business on January 21.  If you fail to do so, we will presume that we have the most complete response that your client is willing to provide at this point and will procee d accordingly.  
The Partners’ offered explanation for why they are unwilling to produce a traditional 
privilege log—simply that this is not a common practice in the regulatory space —is unavailing 
for multiple reasons. The $6.2 Billion transaction the Partners are asking the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission to approve is significantly different in size and character than the typical transaction before the Commission. In addition, a careful review of the information provided to

privilege log,2 underscoring why the Department needs to scrutinize the Partners’ claims of 
privilege.   
Claims of privilege are strictly construed and do not apply to business advice, including 
“regulatory advice for a business purpose.”  In re Polaris, Inc., 967 N.W. 2d 397, 407, 411 (Minn. Dec. 15, 2021) (citations and quotations omitted).  As the party withholding information under a claim of privilege, the Partners have the obligation to “describe the nature ” of the 
withheld material “ in a manner that  … will enable other parties to assess the applicability of the 
privilege or protection.”  Minn. R. Civ. P. 26.02(f)(1). A boilerplate assertion  of privilege is 
inadequate. Bartholomew v. Avalon Cap. Grp. , Inc., 278 F.R.D. 441, 447 (D. Minn. 2011).      
  The Partners’ reasoning for redacting information from responsive documents on grounds other than privilege is both legally and factually unsound. The rules of discovery do not provide any mechanism for a party to redact information from responsive documents during discovery on the grounds of relevance, proportionality, or prejudice. While the Partners cite to two 
unpublished cases from foreign jurisdictions, local  courts have confirmed that responsive 
documents cannot be redacted on the basis of relevance.  See, e.g., Target Corp. v. ACE Am. Ins. 
Co., 576 F. Supp. 3d 609, 620 (D. Minn. 2021); Bartholomew , 278 F.R.D. at  451.   
 
Even if there were a legal basis for redacting information from responsive documents, the 
Partners have not met their burden to show that the claimed redactions are appropriate. As an initial matter, comparing the information revealed during the in camera review with the unredacted information produced demonstrates the arbitrary and inconsistent nature of the redactions.

appear to match the information redacted.4

on the basis that it is prejudicial. Dear Mr. Barlow: 
I write regarding Global Infrastructure Partners’ and Canadian Pension Plan Investment 
Board’s (collectively, “the Partners”) responses to Department information requests 0013 and 
0060, and the Partners’ designation of Ex. DOC-___, SLV-D-6 (“DOC IR SUPP 0011.01 Attach”) 
as Highly Confidential Trade Secret (“HCTS”) data.  
As you know, the Department requested on January 15 that the Partners provide copies of 
all documents responsive to Department information requests 0013 and 0060, with no redactions 
other than claims of privilege properly supported by an updated privilege log, by the close of 
business on Tuesday, January 21. In response, the Partners produced revised responses  that 
continued to redact information on the basis that the omitted information related to regulatory 
compliance. And although the Partners did produce an updated privilege log, it remained deficient. 
Claims of privilege are strictly construed and do not apply to business advice, including 
“regulatory advice for a business purpose.” In re Polaris, Inc. , 967 N.W. 2d 397, 407, 411 (Minn. 
2021). Moreover, as noted in Ms. Arnold’s January 15 correspondence, the Partners’ privilege log 
fails to provide sufficient detail to determine whether the predominant purpose of the redacted 
materials, such as the  was legal advice.1 Id. (“[T]he 
attorney-client privilege ‘applies only if the primary or predominant purpose of the attorney-client 1 Ex. DOC-__, CMA-D-5 at 48 (Addonizio Direct) (DOC IR 0060.01 Attach SUPP HCTS).

consultation is to seek legal advice or assistance.’”). Given this response, it appears that the 
Partners intend to stand on their objections and privilege log. If, however, the Partners do intend 
to provide any further supplementation, they should advise us of their plans no later than close of 
business on Tuesday, February 11.  
 
Second, the Department requests that Partners withdraw their “Highly Confidential Trade 
Secret” designation and make public Ex. DOC-___, SLV-D-6 (“DOC IR SUPP 0011.01 Attach”). 
This document appears to be a basic corporate governance document that any business of 
significance might produce to administer its affairs. More importantly, it is likely the best and only 
document establishing how ALLETE will actually be governed post-Acquisition. To that end, it 
has been repeatedly cited by intervenors in direct testimony, and but-for the Partners’ designation 
it would be a publicly available record.2 Minneapolis Star & Trib. Co. v. Schumacher , 392 N.W.2d 
197, 202 (Minn. 1986) (holding there is a common-law right to inspect and copy civil court 
records); IDT Corp. v. eBay , 709 F.3d 1220, 1222 (8th Cir. 2013) (same). Given the substantial 
public interest implications for the proposed Acquisition and the critical importance of this 
document to understanding how the Acquisition, if approved, will affect ALLETE’s governance, 
the public should have the opportunity to review Ex. DOC-___, SLV-D-6  and independently 
assess the Acquisition’s merits and risks.  
 
The burden is on the Partners to show its designations are appropriate. Given the 
presumption of public access, the Partners have failed to establish that Ex. DOC-___, SLV-D-6 
meets the high threshold for continued designation as HCTS data or the definition of Protected 
Data under the standard protective order. Under the HCTS protective order, only data that meets 
one of the following classifications may be designated as HCTS data: 
 
(a) commercial arrangements or agreements that may affect future 
negotiations or transactions of the disclosing party; 
(b) commercially sensitive investment, financing, or forward-looking 
business plans, analysis, and/or models by or for a disclosing party; 
(c) commercially sensitive data related to specific customers or 
customer groups; or, 
(d) commercially sensitive proprietary information of entities other than 
the disclosing party. 
 
HCTS Protective Order ¶ 3. The Partners have failed to establish that Ex. DOC-___, SLV-D-6 
contains any of these types of HCTS data. The HCTS protective order limits the HCTS designation 
to “information that truly might impose a serious business risk if disseminated without the 
heightened protections.”  HCTS Protective Order at ¶ 6; Star Trib. v. Minnesota Twins P’ship , 659 
N.W.2d 287, 294 (Minn. Ct. App. 2003) (“[T]he burden of demonstrating good cause for each 
challenged document lies with the party seeking protection.”).

The Partners have similarly failed to establish the document contains Protected Data. 
Standard Protective Order ¶ 1. Instead, the Partners parroted the statutory trade secret definition 
and asserted without support that the materials could affect future negotiations or transactions. 
Compare Minn. Stat. § 13.37, subd. 1(b) , with Ex. DOC-___, SLV-D-6 at 3.  Even if the Partners’ 
bald claim that disclosure of Ex. DOC-___, SLV-D-6 could affect future negotiations or 
transactions was supported, that alone would not justify sealing the document from public access. 
See, e.g.,  Healey v. I-Flow, LLC , 282 F.R.D. 211, 215 (D. Minn. 2012) (“[S]ealing must be based 
on current evidence to show how public dissemination of the pertinent materials now would cause 
the competitive harm they claim.”); Kondash v. Kia Motors Am., Inc. , No. 1:15-CV-506, 2018 WL 
770418, at *2 (S.D. Ohio Feb. 7, 2018), aff'd, 767 F. App’x 635 (6th Cir. 2019) (“That a document 
will reveal ‘competitively-sensitive financial and negotiating information’ is not an adequate 
justification for sealing . . . the proponent of closure bears the burden of showing that ‘disclosure 
will work a clearly defined and serious injury.’”). In short, the Partners have failed to carry their 
burden that Ex. DOC-___, SLV-D-6 should not be public.  
 
Please advise whether the Partners will agree to withdraw their claim that Ex. DOC-___, 
SLV-D-6 contains HCTS information and permit the document to be made public no later than 
close of business on Tuesday, February 11.

Dear Mr. Dornfeld : 
I write in response to your letter dated February 7, 2025, requesting that the Partners 
make DOC IR Sup 0011.01 Attach (the Term Sheet) available publicly  and asserting that the 
Partners ’ updated privilege log is deficient.  
At the outset, the Partners have reviewed the Direct Testimony of Ms. Vavro and 
understand this request may be related to the Department’s questions regarding the future 
governance of ALLETE. T o the extent the Department has views regarding the governance 
terms in the Term Sheet, t he Partners would appreciate the opportunity to discuss those views 
with the Department in person . These discussions, hopefully, can help the Partners better 
understand the Department’s concerns and identify ways that they can potentially be 
addressed.  
With respect to the Department’s  specific  requests set forth in the letter dated February 
7, 2025, the Partners respectfully decline both demands .  First, t he Term Sheet contains highly 
sensitive competitive information and thus is appropriately designated as both Trade Secret and  
Highly Confidential Trade Secret data .  The Partners would suffer irreparable harm if it were 
made public because  it undermines their ability to be competitive in other transactions.  
Second, in accordance with Minn. R. Civ. P. 26.(f) , the privilege log describes the nature of the 
documents listed in a manner that, without revealing information itself privileged or protected, 
enables other parties to assess the claim.  As such, it is not deficient  as discussed in more detail 
below.    
DOC IR Supp 0011.01 Attach  
The Minnesota Government Data Practices Act defines trade secret information as data 
that 1) was supplied by the affected organization – here, by the Partners; 2) is the subject of 
efforts by the organization that are reasonable under the circumstances to maintain its secrecy, 
and 3)   derive s independent economic value, actual or potential, from not being generally

known to, and not being readily ascertainable by proper means by, other persons who can 
obtain economic value from its disclosure or use.  Minn. Stat. § 13.37, subd. 1(b). The definition 
is adopted by the  Highly Confidential Trade Secret  Protective Order issued by ALJ McKenzie on 
December  5, 2024.  
The Term Sheet is trade secret information under the Minnesota Government Data 
Practices Act, and therefore protected pursuant to  both Minnesota law and  the Protective Order. 
The Partners are in the business of investing in entities , in whole or part, on their own or with 
other partner -investors , and maintaining the secrecy of the  provisions of the Term Sheet is 
critical to the Partners’ ability to compete in this challenging sector. The Term Sheet describes  a 
number of  critical terms that are heavily nego tiated in such transactions , are proprietary to one 
or more Partners and/or could significantly disadvantage the Partners in future transactions , 
including  [HIGHLY CONFIDENTIAL TRADE SECRET INFORMATION BEGINS …]  
  [… HIGHLY CONFIDENTIAL TRADE SECRET INFORMATION 
ENDS] 
Making  the result of negotiations  in this instance available publicly would irreparably 
harm the Partners as they pursue other transactions, as the businesses seeking investors  and 
the potential partner -investors going -forward would have material information about how each 
Partner seeks to structure their transactions  and what the Partners are or are not willing to 
agree to on critical commercial and governance terms , placing the Partners at a significant 
competitive disadvantage in future transactions.  Because of its nature as a highly negotiated 
document  with bespoke and institutionally  sensitive  terms between the Partners, it is not a 
“basic corporate governance document” as suggest ed in the February 7 letter .  
Further, as we have explained in prior discussions , the Partners have taken substantial 
efforts to maintain the secrecy of the Term Sheet  precisely  because its disclosure would 
irreparably  harm the Partners , including their  ability to compete for similar investment 
opportunities in the future.  Until it was produced for discovery in this proceeding, the Term 
Sheet was never  provided to any person that was not employed by or representing the 
Partners, and was never disclosed publicly in any venue.  The Term Sheet is trade secret 
information under the Minnesota Government Data Practices Act and the assertion to the 
contrary is without merit or legal basis.  
The Term Sheet also is Highly Confidential Trade Secret (“ HCTS ”) information . The 
HCTS Protective Order issued on December 16, 2024, provides that HCTS information includes 
information related to “commercial arrangements or agreements that may affect future 
negotiations or transactions of the disclosing party.” Perhaps no other document fits this 
definition more precisely than the Term Sheet, and for good reason:  this language —which the 
Department agreed to and jointly recommended to ALJ McKenzie —was draf ted specifically to 
protect this  type of  document . As described above, t he Term Sheet contains  the highly -
confidential commercial arrangements between the Partners, and its disclosure would affect

many  future negotiations or transactions of each of the Partners , either with each other or with 
other entities  who would , in effect, have a roadmap to negotiations with a Partner and each 
Partner’s competitive sensitivities, if the Term Sheet were publicly disclosed . In sum, public 
disclosure would cause irreparable harm to the Partners.  
 Finally, while we understand the Department’s interest in governance matters  as part of 
the broader assessment of the acquisition , that interest does not mean that the protections 
afforded by the Minnesota Data Practices Act and the HCTS Protective Order must be sacrificed.  
There is nothing about the regulatory process that requires no t public data to be made public, 
and in fact Commission rules provide that “[n] othing in this chapter  [7829]  requires public 
disclosure of protected data or any disclosure of privileged data. ” Minn. R. 7829.0500.    Both 
the Department and the Commission routinely review non -public information in executing their 
responsibilities , and we have full confidence in their ability to do so in this case consistent with 
the protections afforded under Min nesota law  and by the HCTS Protective Order that the 
Department agreed to . Indeed, the direct testimony submitted by the Department and by 
intervenors in this proceeding reflects their ability to do so . Further, the Partners intend to be 
responsive to the Department’s request to provide more information about governance in our 
Rebuttal Testimony.  
DOC IRs 0013 and 0060  
The Partners do not agree that their updated privilege log is deficient .  
To the extent the Minnesota Rules of Civil Procedure are applicable here, Minn. R. Civ. P. 
26.(f) requires that a party asserting privilege describe the nature of the documents “in a 
manner that, without revealing information itself privileged or protected, will enable other 
parties to assess the applicability of the privilege o r protection.” The Partners have made this 
showing. For each redaction in the relevant documents, the Partners have identified that the 
redacted information is legal advice and not b usiness advice; identified the general topic of the 
legal advice; identified the legal counsel that provided the advice; and identified that the advice 
was received by the relevant Partner and not disclosed to anyone else. In addition, the privilege 
log clearly states that the identified work product was prepared in anticipation of litigation – 
including this regulatory proceeding.  
The February 7, 2025 , letter appears  to contend that privilege redactions are 
inappropriate because the “information [is] related to regulatory compliance ,” citing In re 
Polaris, Inc. , 967 N.W.2d 397 (Minn. 2021).  We do not agree.  Polaris  does not establish a 
blanket rule that regulatory advice is not privileged; rather, it applied the long -standing rule 
that ordinary business advice is not privileged, while legal advice is privileged, and considered 
whether the entirety of a document conta ining both lega l advice and business advice can be 
protected as privileged.  Id. at 410 -11. That analysis is not applicable here, as the Partners are 
not asserting that the entire contents of these documents is privileged or that the predominant 
purpose of the documents is legal advice. Rather, the Partners have appropriately limited the 
redactions for privilege to those portions of the documents that contain legal advice —precisely 
as required by the Supreme Cour t in Polaris . As explained in the privilege log , the pages labeled 
“Preliminary 100 -Day Plan Priorities” “reflect near -term action items to address legal and 
compliance issues and risks, as identified by internal and external counsel during the diligence 
process.” This content is legal advice and  its protection is supported by  Polaris , which confirms

The Honorable Megan J. McKenzie  Administrative Law Judge  Office of Administrative Hearings  PO Box 64620  
St. Paul, MN 55164- 0620  
 
Re:          
 
In the Matter of the Petition of Minnesota 
Power for the Acquisition of ALLETE by 
Canada Pension Plan Investment Board and 
Global Infrastructure Partners  OAH No. 25 -2500 -40339  
  MPUC Docket No . E-015/PA -24-198 
 Dear Judge McKenzie:  
 
I write to respond to the letter filed by GIP’s counsel late on Friday, February 7,
 2025.  The purpose 
of this letter is to confirm to Your Honor and other parties that CUB has taken this matter very 
seriously , that we are cooperat ing with affected parties , and that we have otherwise  taken action 
to comply with Your Honor’s protective orders  in this docket . 
 Last week,  one of CUB’s witnesses,  Mr. Hempling,  uploaded what he thought was a public version 
of his direct testimony to a personal website. Later that same evening, Mr. Hempling posted , on a 
second website,  a link to where that testimony was availab le. Within approximately fifteen minutes 
of Mr. Hempling posting this link, I noticed the posted version of his testimony included information 
marked highly confidential trade secret that had not yet been redacted from the testimony.  
 
I immediately contacted Mr. Hempling to inform him of the error, and Mr. Hempling immediately took action to remove access to the testimony. I then  called outside counsel for GIP after regular 
business hours —and emailed both him and outside counsel for ALLETE —alerting them to the 
inadvertent disclosure. In the time since, Mr. Hempling and I have cooperated with requests for information that affected parties have shared with u s. 
 
Both Mr. Hempling and I deeply regret this inadvertent disclosure and sincerely apologize for it. 
We will continue to cooperate with affected parties as well as with any requests or instructions 
from Your Honor relating to this issue.  
 
Sincerely,  
 
/s/ Brian Edstrom

Dear Judge McKenzie : 
We write to notify Your Honor  that Canada Pension Plan Investment Board and Global 
Infrastructure Management, LLC (together, the “Partners”) , along with Minnesota Power,  were 
notified late yesterday by the Citizen’s Utility Board of Minnesota (“CUB”) that their expert witness , 
Scott Hempling  of Scott Hempling, Attorney at Law LLC , breached your December 13, 2024 
Protective Order for Highly Confidential Trade Secret Data (the “HCTS Protective Order”)  to which 
he is a signatory.   
Unfortunately, CUB disclosed that Mr. Hempling published on at least two different websites , 
including one that touts more than 1 billion members,  links to an unredacted Word version of his 
Direct Testimony containing Highly Confidential Trade Secret (“HCTS”) Information.  We have 
been told that  the unredacted testimony has since been taken down  and are undertaking to 
confirm this . The parties to the Acquisition  are in the process of assessing the appropriate remedy 
and sanction for  Mr. Hempling’s breach of  the HCTS Protective Order  and reserve all rights in that 
regard .   
  
The Honorable Megan McKenzie  
February 7, 2025  
Page 2 
 
 
For now , the Partners call upon  all parties to exercise the utmost diligence and rigor in the ir use 
of HCTS Information consistent with the procedures outlined in the HCTS Protective Order, the 
Minnesota Data Practices Act and all ethical obligations applicable to attorneys appearing in this 
proceeding.  
Sincerely,
